al sermon compilations, exempla, and pastoral guides could have significantly shaped the perceptions, attitudes, and- perhaps - actions of fourteenth- and fifteenth-century priests. Shedding light on the mental universe of the late medieval parish, this study offers important new insights into the reality of how priests perceived and fulfilledtheir spiritual obligations to the women they served. BETH ALLISON BARR is Assistant Professor of European Women's History at Baylor University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChurch work with womenxEnglandxHistory. 0aChurch work with womenzEnglandxHistory. 0aPastoral carexEnglandxHistory. 0aPastoral carezEnglandxHistory. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aFestial.  aInstructions for Parish Priests.  aJohn Mirk.  aMiddle Ages.  afemale parishioners.  alate medieval parish.  aparish priests.  apastoral vernacular literature.  areligious texts.  aspiritual obligations.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846156663?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846156663423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846156663/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles